### Mutex in Rust

`Mutex<T>` provides mutual exclusion for sharing data across threads. Only one thread can access the data at a time.

---

### Mutex Features

| Feature | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Lock | Blocks until exclusive access is obtained |
| Try lock | Returns immediately (success or would block) |
| Poisoning | If a thread panics while holding the lock, the mutex is poisoned |
| RAII guard | Lock is automatically released when `MutexGuard` drops |

---

### Examples

```rust
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};
use std::thread;

let counter = Arc::new(Mutex::new(0));
let mut handles = vec![];

for _ in 0..10 {
    let counter = Arc::clone(&counter);
    let handle = thread::spawn(move || {
        let mut num = counter.lock().unwrap();
        *num += 1;
    });
    handles.push(handle);
}

for handle in handles {
    handle.join().unwrap();
}

println!("Result: {}", *counter.lock().unwrap());  // 10

// Try lock (non-blocking)
if let Ok(mut guard) = mutex.try_lock() {
    *guard = 42;
} else {
    println!("Mutex is locked by another thread");
}
```

> **Key Point:** Always use `Arc<Mutex<T>>` for shared mutable state across threads. The lock is released when the `MutexGuard` goes out of scope. Handle mutex poisoning by checking if `.lock()` returns an `Err` and recovering if needed.

codeExample:
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};
use std::thread;

fn main() {
    let shared_data = Arc::new(Mutex::new(Vec::new()));
    let mut handles = vec![];

    for i in 0..5 {
        let data = Arc::clone(&shared_data);
        handles.push(thread::spawn(move || {
            let mut vec = data.lock().unwrap();
            vec.push(i);
            println!("Thread {} added", i);
        }));
    }

    for handle in handles {
        handle.join().unwrap();
    }

    println!("Final data: {:?}", shared_data.lock().unwrap());
}
